        <li data-comment-id="comment_blogAndPostId/blog/comment/1380-1458-556" data-comment-wp-id="556"  parent-id="" class="comment level0 collapsable" data-badges-advoice="">
            <div class="entity_block">
                <a class="avatar" href="http://blogs.forbes.com/people/gama/">
                    <img src="http://l.yimg.com/a/i/identity2/profile_192b.png" alt="Gama Xul" />
                </a>



                <a class="user_name" href="http://blogs.forbes.com/people/gama/">
                    Gama Xul
                </a>


   		<span class="timestamp">5 months ago</span>
    	</div>

    	<div class="comment_content">
    		<p>It is not so important which companies control what, as it is that any company can control anything. This is of no concern to anyone as long as taxes and fees on the public are not dependant on corporate policy or relation to government. Sadly, they have structured it as relative, so we have a lot of work ahead of us to separate government from private sector interests. For instance, if I want to live in a house I own, or rent it to others; that produces a vast difference in yearly taxes. But it shouldn’t. The fact that there is a significant difference means that there is a profit margin being truncated by government policy to trap classes within their monetary confines. Government shouldn’t have any say in the matter of personal finance or profit, and it is most likely due to the bigger companies aiming to lock smaller businesses out of their profit markets. This is merely factual observation. Anything that is profitable is heavily regulated, and that is the problem. If you dispose of regulation, you destroy the controls corporations have manufactured. Deregulation is the key to real profit. Down with crony capitalism! Support real capitalism. NO REGULATION!</p> 
<p>If you look at any Fortune 500 company, they perform illegal activities and hope not to be noticed; but when they are discovered, they are slapped on the wrist and pay a fine that is disproportionate in effect than if a small business was caught doing the same. Therefore, the regulations favor the corporations that designed them; thus you have corruption. Is it too far to think that your “representatives” have been bought and paid for? Why can no one else deduce these scenarios?</p> 
<p>Capitalists have been around since people believed in owning items as property. They aren’t the problem. Regulation is the problem.</p> 
<p>-Gama Xul</p>

    	</div>



